Note:
Regression test for stage1 codegen bug #391: cross-module struct return
field access. Stage1 used to emit
  [CODEGEN ERROR] Could not resolve struct type for field 'l'
  (object declared as 'Integer') on variable 'lab_black' in function
  'test_lab_black'
when handling `Let y be Lab.lab_black()` followed by `y.l`.

Root cause: codegen_get_expression_type for EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL needs to
look up the callee's declared return type in the imported (merged) function
table. When that lookup fails, the Let-be statement falls back to
codegen_add_variable which defaults the variable's type to "Integer". With
two or more struct types in the program that share the same field name,
codegen_find_struct_type_for_field's Pass 2 (field-name dispatch) cannot
disambiguate and returns 0, triggering the "could not resolve struct type"
error.

Fix verification: this test imports a module that declares a struct type
and a function returning that struct, then accesses a field on the
returned value through a single chained Let / field-access. The compile
must produce non-empty .s output and the runtime result must match the
declared field value.
:End Note

Import "tests/compiler/stage1/test_cross_module_struct_return_lab.runa" as Lab

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let y be Lab.lab_black()
    Display y.l
    Display "\n"
    Note: Exit code = field value minus the canonical Lab-black L value the
    Note: fixture stores in lab_black (42 in this contrived dataset; the
    Note: fixture predates the proper Lab colour-space constants).  Returns
    Note: 0 only when stage1 correctly resolved the imported struct type
    Note: and read the L field; any miscompile flows a non-zero rc to the
    Note: harness.
    Return y.l minus 42
End Process
